# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1768-british-general-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1768-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] The **1708 British general election** was the first general election to be held after the Acts of Union had united the Parliaments of England and Scotland.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] The election saw the Whigs gain a majority in the House of Commons, and by November the Whig-dominated parliament had succeeded in pressuring the Queen into accepting the Whig Junto into government for the first time since the late 1690s.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] The Whigs only able to take partial control of the government, however, owing to the continued presence of the moderate Tory Godolphin in the cabinet (as Lord High Treasurer) and the opposition of the Queen.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] Contests were held in 95 of the 269 English and Welsh constituencies and 28 of the 45 Scottish constituencies.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] Following the election, Whig MP Lord Somers was appointed as Lord President of the Council.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] However, moderate Tory Lord Godolphin remained as Lord High Treasurer and the Godolphin–Marlborough ministry remained in place.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] In England, there were 513 MPs elected from 245 constituencies (203 boroughs, 40 counties, and 2 universities).
[src:1768-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] In Wales, there were 24 MPs from 24 constituencies.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] In Scotland, there were 45 MPs from 45 constituencies (30 counties and 15 burghs).
[src:1768-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] The first general election held since the Union took place between 30 April 1708 and 7 July 1708.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] At this period elections did not take place at the same time in every constituency.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] The returning officer in each county or borough fixed the precise date (see hustings for details of the conduct of the elections).
[src:1768-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] In England and Wales, the Whigs took 268 seats and the Tories took 225, with 20 unclassified.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1708-british-general-election] The 45 in Scotland could be classified as ministerial supporters.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The **1710 British general election** produced a landslide victory for the Tories.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The election came in the wake of the prosecution of Henry Sacheverell, which had led to the collapse of the previous government led by Godolphin and the Whig Junto.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] In November 1709 the clergyman Henry Sacheverell had delivered a sermon fiercely criticising the government's policy of toleration for Protestant dissenters and attacking the personal conduct of the ministers.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The government had Sacheverell impeached, and he was narrowly found guilty but received only a light sentence, making the government appear weak and vindictive.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The trial enraged a large section of the population, and riots in London led to attacks on dissenting places of worship and cries of "Church in Danger".
[src:1768-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The government's unpopularity was further increased by its enthusiasm for the war with France, as peace talks with the French king Louis XIV had broken down over the government's insistence that the Bourbons hand over the Spanish throne to the Habsburgs.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The Tories' policy of pursuing peace appealed to a country worn out by constant war.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] Queen Anne, disliking the Junto and sensing that the government could not survive long, gradually replaced it with a Tory ministry throughout the summer of 1710.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The election was bitterly contested in almost all the counties and "open" boroughs, even when a poll was not held.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] Contests occurred in 131 constituencies in England and Wales; approximately half of all English and Welsh constituencies.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The overwhelming Tory victory surprised few, and following the election most remaining Whigs resigned from office.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The new government was led by the moderate Tory Robert Harley who was unpopular among the more partisan Tories.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] Harley's ministry faced increasing pressure from the extremists whose position in Parliament had been enormously strengthened by the result.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] See 1796 British general election for details.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The constituencies used were the same throughout the existence of the Parliament of Great Britain.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The general election was held between 2 October 1710 and 16 November 1710.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1710-british-general-election] The returning officer in each county or parliamentary borough fixed the precise date (see hustings for details of the conduct of the elections).
[src:1768-british-general-election/1713-british-general-election] The **1713 British general election** was held on 22 August 1713 to 12 November 1713, to elect members of the House of Commons, the lower house of the Parliament of Great Britain.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1713-british-general-election] It produced further gains for the governing Tory party.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1713-british-general-election] The government remained popular with the electorate, however, having entered into peace negotiations ending the War of the Spanish Succession and later agreeing on the Treaty of Utrecht.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1713-british-general-election] The Tories consequently made further gains against the Whigs, making Harley's job even more difficult.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1713-british-general-election] Contests were held in 94 constituencies in England and Wales, some 35 per cent of the total, reflecting a decline in partisan tension and the Whigs' belief that they were unlikely to win anyway.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1713-british-general-election] The general election was held between 22 August 1713 and 12 November 1713.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1715-british-general-election] The **1715 British general election** was held on 22 January 1715 to 9 March 1715, to elect members of the House of Commons, the lower house of the Parliament of Great Britain.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1715-british-general-election] It returned members to serve in the House of Commons of the 5th Parliament of Great Britain to be held, after the 1707 merger of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1715-british-general-election] In October 1714, soon after George I had arrived in London after ascending to the throne, he dismissed the Tory cabinet and replaced it with one almost entirely composed of Whigs, as they were responsible for securing his succession.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1715-british-general-election] The election of 1715 saw the Whigs win an overwhelming majority in the House of Commons, and afterwards virtually all Tories in central or local government were purged, leading to a period of Whig ascendancy lasting almost fifty years during which Tories were almost entirely excluded from office.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1715-british-general-election] The Whigs then moved to impeach Robert Harley, the former Tory first minister.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1715-british-general-election] After he was imprisoned in the Tower of London for two years, the case ultimately ended with his acquittal in 1717.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1715-british-general-election] The general election was held between 22 January 1715 and 9 March 1715.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] The **1722 British general election** elected members to serve in the House of Commons of the 6th Parliament of Great Britain.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] This was the fifth such election since the merger of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1707.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] Thanks to the Septennial Act 1715, which swept away the maximum three-year life of a parliament created by the Meeting of Parliament Act 1694, it followed seven years after the previous election, that of 1715.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] The election was fiercely fought, with contests taking place in more than half of the constituencies, which was unusual for the time.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] In the midst of the election, word came from France of a Jacobite plot aimed at an imminent coup d'état.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] Led by Francis Atterbury, Bishop of Rochester, Lord North and Grey, and other Tory opponents of Walpole, this was later known as the "Atterbury Plot".
[src:1768-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] Previously election results had broadly reflected the opinion of at least the minority of adult males who had the vote, although the system had always been subject to the influence of corruption and patronage.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] However, now that one-party government had been established, those influences could be used systematically to ensure the governing party's victory.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] This election set the pattern for much of the rest of the eighteenth century; as partisan feeling began to decline during the years of the Whig oligarchy, the rigging of elections became ever easier, so that British governments could almost always guarantee victory.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1722-british-general-election] The general election was held between 19 March 1722 and 9 May 1722.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1727-british-general-election] The **1727 British general election** returned members to serve in the House of Commons of the 7th Parliament of Great Britain to be summoned, after the merger of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1707.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1727-british-general-election] The election was triggered by the death of King George I; at the time, it was the convention to hold new elections following the succession of a new monarch.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1727-british-general-election] A group known as the Patriot Whigs, led by William Pulteney, who were disenchanted with Robert Walpole's government and believed he was betraying Whig principles, had been formed prior to the election.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1727-british-general-election] Bolingbroke and Pulteney had not expected the next election to occur until 1729, and were consequently caught unprepared.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1727-british-general-election] They failed to make any gains against the government party.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1727-british-general-election] The general election was held between 14 August 1727 and 17 October 1727.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1727-british-general-election] At this period, elections did not take place at the same time in every constituency.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1734-british-general-election] The **1734 British general election** returned members to serve in the House of Commons of the 8th Parliament of Great Britain to be summoned, after the merger of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1707.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1734-british-general-election] Robert Walpole's increasingly unpopular Whig government lost ground to the Tories and the opposition Whigs, but still had a secure majority in the House of Commons.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1734-british-general-election] The Patriot Whigs under William Pulteney were joined in opposition by a group of Whig members led by Lord Cobham.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1734-british-general-election] They were known as the Cobhamites, or 'Cobham's Cubs'.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1734-british-general-election] The general election was held between 22 April 1734 and 6 June 1734.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The **1768 British general election** returned members to serve in the House of Commons of the 13th Parliament of Great Britain to be held, after the merger of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1707.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The election took place amid continuing shifts within politics which had occurred with the accession of George III in 1760.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The Tories who had long been in parliamentary opposition having not won an election since 1713 had disintegrated with its former parliamentarians gravitating between the various Whig factions, the Ministry, or continued political independence as a Country Gentleman.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] No Tory party existed at this point, though the label of Tory was occasionally used as a political insult by opposition groups against the government.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Since the last general election the Whigs had lost cohesion and had split into various factions aligned with leading political figures.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The leading figures around the period of the prior election, namely the Earl of Bute, the Duke of Newcastle and the Earl of Chatham, were all retiring from political life for various reasons.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] While Chatham remained the nominal figurehead leader of the Ministry, the administration was centred on the First Lord of the Treasury; the Duke of Grafton, and his leader in the commons; Lord North.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The election took place during a lull in political conflict, with there being a lack of any real political debate over policy or principle between the main factions.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The major opposition factions, the Rockingham Whigs under the Marquess of Rockingham and the Grenvillites under George Grenville owed their origins and strength to the periods when their respective leaders had led Ministries in the early-to-mid part of the decade.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Owing to these conditions the exact makeup of the new House of Commons was unclear, though estimates suggest that the opposition gained slightly on the Ministry in the months immediately after the election.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Potentially the most important part of the election was the election of the radical John Wilkes in the metropolitan constituency of Middlesex.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Wilkes's election triggered a major political crisis, and marked the beginning of political radicalism in Britain.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] During the lifetime of the 12th Parliament of Great Britain five men held office as Prime Minister leading to the description of the period as one of ministerial instability.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] By 1766 the successive ministries of Newcastle, Bute, Grenville and Rockingham had collapsed, resulting in the King, George III appointed William Pitt, subsequently created the Earl of Chatham as Prime Minister.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] George III in commissioning Chatham to form an administration had sought to find a stable Administration which would command the confidence of both the Crown and Parliament, something that Chatham appeared to possess unlike his two immediate predecessors.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] By 1767 Chatham had increasingly alienated the hitherto cordial Rockinghamites through his dismissal of Lord Edgcumbe as Treasurer of the Household.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] While some Rockinghamites, namely Henry Seymour Conway remained part of the Ministry, many others who did not hold cabinet-level offices resigned their positions in response.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] This, coupled with the replacement of these individuals by individuals formerly close to Bute assisted in increasing the unpopularity of the Ministry.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] To further complicate matters the Ministry was divided over what would become the Townshend Duties, proposed by Chancellor of the Exchequer Charles Townshend in relation to the American colonies.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Chatham, who was sympathetic to the American colonists and their concerns, suffered a nervous breakdown in early 1767, prompting Grafton to assume increasing levels of authority within the government.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] In response the opposition factions had moved to form a union among themselves which only further amplified the problems of the Ministry.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] After unsuccessful negotiations between the Ministry and the Rockinghamites, the Bedfordites joined the Ministry with several Bedfordites, namely Lord Gower, Viscount Weymouth and the Earl of Hillsborough becoming members of the cabinet.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Over the course of the summer of 1767 Conway was gradually superseded as the government's Commons leader by Townshend who appeared in the political ascendant until his premature death in September 1767.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] He was ultimately replaced by Lord North who became increasingly prominent within the Ministry.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] By this point a general election was increasingly on the horizon resulting in numerous Independent Members of Parliament reducing their attendance, while affording opposition MPs the opportunity to raise popular political questions ahead of facing their electors.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Parliament ultimately dissolved on 11 March 1768 ahead of the general election.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The size and strength of Parliamentary factions during the lifetime of the 12th Parliament of Great Britain were rather fluid.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The 1761 general election had returned a sizable Whig majority with the opposition formed by a cohort of over 100 Tories and a number of malcontent Independent Whigs notably including Francis Dashwood and Lord Strange.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] While the exact point of the demise of the Tory party is debated among historians of 18th-century politics, it is clear that by the end of the Parliamentary term no Tory party existed.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] While several dozen Tories did remain in the Commons even as late as the early 19th-century, their number gradually dwindled and no coherent unified Tory 'party' can be argued to have existed after the 1761 general election.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] By the time of the Chatham Administration it was clear that politics was formed along factional rather than party lines.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] An indication of the strength and state of parties in the period before the election is indicated in parliamentary lists created by Rockingham in November 1766, Townshend in January 1767, and Newcastle in March 1767.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] These lists differ greatly in various aspects especially among the classification of Independent Country Gentlemen ex-Tories, though the lists do demonstrate that the Ministry held around 220 seats, the Opposition factions around 150, while around 180 Members were Independents of varying degrees.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The general election was held over a period between 16 March 1768 and 6 May 1768.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] During this period elections did not take place at the same time in every constituency.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Parliamentary oppositions during this period never had a significant chance of winning power outright at a general election where the government's patronage and ability to hand out sinecure appointments and pensions were enough to maintain power.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Indeed during this period no government was ever defeated for re-election.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Little material exists for the Ministry's activities with Grafton's papers being relatively bare, and no papers relating to the secret service accounts or those of the government's election agents have been found to date.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Despite the clear advantage afforded to the Ministry, the inertness of Grafton ensured that the election in various constituencies was far more competitive that it realistically should have been.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] This was seen in various constituencies where the Treasury nominally held significant influence but due to Grafton's inaction, Lord Newcastle was able to maintain a hold on these seats in favour of the Rockingham Whigs at the general election.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The increasing competitiveness of the election was demonstrated by the fact that 83 constituencies went to the polls, an increase of 30 on the figure from 1761.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] 8 contests occurred in English county constituencies, 60 in English borough constituencies of varying sizes, 1 at Oxford University, 5 in Welsh constituencies, and 9 in Scottish seats.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] This was therefore among the most competitive general elections of the period with borough managers being seen to have increasingly difficult times managing smaller boroughs against the attacks of outsiders and insurgent candidates.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The contest in Essex was still fought along nominal Tory and Whig partisan lines, as Edmund Burke noted 'on the business of a century ago'.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Ancestral partisan alignments had persisted to the point of fossilization, though until a decade prior the constituency had been a Tory stronghold.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] At a by-election in 1759 the Essex Whigs had been so weak that they had resolved to run a Tory under the Whig label.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The confusion of the period of Ministerial instability is reflected in a by-election in 1763 when the local Tories ran John Conyers and the Whigs ran John Luther who both professed themselves to be supporters of the Grenvillite faction.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] At the by-election Luther narrowly prevailed over Conyers by a margin of just over one-hundred votes.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The contest in 1768 was confusing and featured a contest between supporters of the government, Luther and the ex-Tory Sir William Maynard who were opposed by the remnants of the local Tories, who ran Jacobin Houblon, Jr. and Eliab Harvey as their candidates for the by-election.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] At the poll the Tory candidates were soundly defeated with local landlord influences assisting the pro-government Essex Whigs in finally defeating the old Tory interest in the constituency.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The City of London was among the most politically conscious constituencies in the nation with a sizable franchise and its own elective local government system that enabled the constituency to be particularly susceptible to political movements.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Politics had a class-element to an extent, with larger merchants leaning towards the government, while smaller merchants, artisans, crafters and shopkeepers who lacked government financial connections had traditionally supported local 'Patriot' Opposition Whigs and Tories.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Pitt had enjoyed considerable support in the City prior to his resignation from the government in 1761 and his failure to cultivate support.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Opposition to government economic policies had enable the slow increase in anti-government and 'radical' political sympathies among voters.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The contest in 1768 saw all four incumbents run for re-election, joined by American merchant and Rockinghamite Barlow Trecothick, independent John Paterson, and the last minute bid by radical John Wilkes who had recently returned from exile in France.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Wilkes had neither a programme nor a party and was unable to gain a foothold during the election.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Ultimately Harley, Ladbroke and Beckford were easily returned, while Glyn was narrowly defeated by Trecothick.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Wilkes polled just over a thousand votes in this constituency.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The most prominent constituency contest of the election was that in Middlesex.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The constituency had since a 1750 by-election been held as a compromise between the local Tories and Whigs by Whig William Beauchamp-Proctor and Tory George Cooke.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The two had held their seats without a contest at the 1754 and 1761 general elections with the assumption that this tranquility would likely be maintained in the coming 1768 election.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] In February 1768 radical John Wilkes had returned from his self-imposed exile in France where he had remained for four years after being convinced for libel and blasphemy.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Wilkes' financial situation had become desperate necessitating him to return to reclaim a seat at Westminster.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Wilkes' attempt to win one of the four seats in the City of London had fallen considerably short several days prior.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Undeterred he opted to campaign in the neighbouring Middlesex county seat, challenging the Courtier Whig Beauchamp-Proctor and the ailing, gout-ridden Chathamite Cooke.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] With around two-thousand electors turning out to vote, Wilkes topped the poll and unseated Beauchamp-Proctor, being returned with Cooke.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Some residual Tory support may explain Wilkes' success with the *St.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] James Chronicle* noting that Wilkes and Cooke polled well in the Tory east of the constituency where small freeholders were prevalent.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Wilkes' support from the old Tory Half Moon Club and the Independent Electors of Westminster, in addition to his employing of blue ribbons for his campaign, are telling.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Regardless of the psephological points, Wilkes had polled strongly, much to the chagrin of prominent political figures.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Wilkes' election prompted the Ministry to unseat him only for Wilkes to win a series of three by-elections, until finally the Ministry controversially sat a rival, Henry Luttrell as the new Member of Parliament instead.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The constituency where the traditional party alignments persisted the longest and most strongly was Oxford University.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The constituency had been resolutely Tory in its politics since before the Hanoverian succession and jealously guarded its political independence and Tory identity, leading Horace Walpole to brand Oxfordshire 'a little Kingdom of Jacobitism'.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Since a 1762 by-election the representation of the constituency had been shared by two old Tories, William Bagot and Roger Newdigate, who both enjoyed prior Parliamentary experience before being returned by the University.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The University Whigs were well aware that the stood little chance of wrestling control of the seat from the Tories except if the Tory interest was divided.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] An opportunity for a contest emerged after Bagot's death in spring 1768.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The Whigs desired to run Charles Jenkinson, a former close ally of Bute as their candidate.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Jenkinson hailed from a Tory family but had played a role in the infamous Oxfordshire election of 1754 which had soured Tories considerably towards him.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The Tory meanwhile returned William Dolben as a stopgap MP until the general election, Dolben would meanwhile win office in the general election in Northamptonshire.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] At the general election the popular and respected Newdigate's position was secure, while there was a genuine contest for the second seat.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The Tories were initially split between the candidacies of Amersham (UK Parliament constituency) MP William Drake, Sr. and squire Francis Page.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Yet the fear of a split and the victory of Jenkinson resolved them to unify behind Page.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The Tories were bolstered by a fear that a victory by a pro-government candidate, namely Jenkinson would result in the constituency losing its independence and become a government borough.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Additional candidates included Thomas Fitzmaurice and the jurist George Hay whose quixotic bid mystified many and attracted little support.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Fitzmaurice, shortly before polling, dropped out and backed Page after being assured of support at a future election.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Ultimately the Tory interest would hold firm at the University with Newdigate and Page being easily returned over Jenkinson and Hay.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The overall result of the general election remains unclear to historians owing to the confused nature of politics and partisanship during the 1760s.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Nevertheless some precise electoral facts are clear.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] 167 Members of Parliament were returned who had not formerly sat in Parliament.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Of these Members during their first years in office, they tended to lean towards the Opposition as seen by their stances with relation to the Middlesex election affair.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Yet over the course of the Parliamentary term this preference began to wear off resulting in the Ministry, especially after Lord North assumed its leadership in 1770; being assured of the confidence of the Commons on most matters.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] That Grafton's ineptitude cost the Ministry various winnable seats and extra support in Parliament is demonstrated by the clear fact that the Opposition, be it factional or Independent MPs, increased in size to some degree as a result of the 1768 general election.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Figures for several of the factions and tendencies in the Commons are available.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Around 140 factional MPs are estimated to have been returned.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] Of this figure it is known that the Rockinghamites increased their number of MPs from 54 to 57.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The Grenvillites entered the election with 41 MPs and incurred nineteen loses and gained ten seats, winning them 31 seats.
[src:1768-british-general-election/1768-british-general-election] The Bedfordites according to an overview of their MPs held around 23 seats prior to the election and ultimately won around 20 seats.
